    <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto py-8 px-4 grid items-center grid-cols-1 gap-y-16 gap-x-8 sm:px-6 sm:py-8 lg:max-w-7xl lg:px-8 lg:grid-cols-2">
        
      <div>
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-gray-900 sm:text-4xl">Sense of Community</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-500">
            Reddit's sense of community is unique in that it is based on the concept of "subreddits." Subreddits are essentially smaller communities within the greater Reddit community that are based around a specific topic. For example, there is a subreddit for everything from funny cat pictures to political discussion. This allows users to find like-minded people more easily and creates a more tight-knit community feel.

            In contrast, Instagram, Twitter, and Snapchat are all based around a more general idea of sharing photos, thoughts, or experiences with others. There is less of a sense of community on these platforms, as users are not typically grouped together based on common interests. However, all of these platforms still provide an addictive and engaging experience for users.
            
            What makes all of these platforms addictive and engaging is the constant stream of new content that is always available. Whether it's new photos on Instagram, new tweets on Twitter, or new snaps on Snapchat, there is always something new to see. This constant flow of content keeps users coming back for more, and ultimately creates a very addictive experience.        </p>    
            
      </div>
